    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-02-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-02-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="91"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Chentung Liang-Cheng</persName> to
                        Mr. <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-02-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 13, 1904</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear</hi> Mr. <hi rend="smallcaps">Secretary</hi>: I beg
                    to inclose herewith for the files of your Department copies of two telegrams
                    from the Waiwu Pu, dated the 12th instant, relative to the neutrality of China
                    in the present conflict between Japan and Russia,<note n="a" xml:id="d91fna"
                        >Printed under neutrality proclamations, <ref target="#pg_17">p.
                        17</ref>.</note> the contents of which I communicated to you this
                    morning.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Chentung Liang-Cheng.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
